Murray & Roberts (M&R) will recommend that its shareholders reject German’s ATON GmbH’s buyout offer as it is “opportunistic” and undervalues the South African engineering and construction company, it said on Tuesday. ATON, the investment vehicle of German investor Lutz Helmig, which already owns a third of M&R, offered to buy the rest of M&R’s shares at a cash offer price of 15 rands ($1.29) per share – a 56% premium to M&R closing price last Thursday. Shares in M&R fell 6.06% to 13.18 rand at 11:57 GMT after the company released its statement. ($1 = 11.6668 rand).